04578nam a22006495i 9780292796263DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927962637 a10.7560/7069032doi  a(DE-B1597)588298  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aJK1991.5.T4D67 2006 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a324.7/8/097642221 aDorsey, Margaret E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPachangas :bBorderlands Music, U.S. Politics, and Transnational Marketing /cMargaret E. Dorsey. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (247 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I. Political Pachangas, Marketing, and Music -- tONE. A History and Style of Association: Music, Pachangas, and Politics in South Texas -- tTWO. Marketing Pachangas: The Budgirls -- tTHREE. Budweiser’s Hispanic Scholarship Fund Fiesta Extravaganza -- tFOUR. Out of a Social Gathering, Music: Galvanizing Persons into Politics -- tPART II. Democracy and the Borderlands: Two Versions -- tFIVE. Pachanga Moves: A Local Republican and a National Democratic Gathering -- tSIX. Ace Hardware: National Corporate Marketers Learn How the Locals Do It -- tSEVEN. A Private Event for a Public Servant: “Mr. Vega” Meets Modernity -- tCONCLUSIONS -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA uniquely Tejano version of the old-fashioned political barbeque, the traditional South Texas pachanga allowed politicians to connect with voters in a relaxed setting where all could enjoy live music and abundant food and drink along with political speeches and dealmaking. Today's pachanga still combines politics, music, and votes—along with a powerful new element. Corporate sponsorships have transformed the pachanga into a major marketing event, replete with celebrity performers and product giveaways, which can be recorded and broadcast on TV or radio to vastly increase the reach of the political—and the commercial—messages. This book explores the growing convergence of politics, transnational marketing, and borderlands music in the South Texas pachanga. Anthropologist Margaret Dorsey has observed some one hundred pachangas and interviewed promoters, politicians, artists, and local people. She investigates how candidates and corporations market their products to Hispanic consumers, as well as how the use of traditional music for marketing is altering traditional forms such as the corrido. Her multifaceted study also shows clearly that the lines of influence run both ways—while corporate culture is transforming the traditions of the border, Tejano voters/consumers only respond to marketing appeals (whether for politicians or products) that resonate with their values and the realities of their lives. Far from being an example of how transnational marketing homogenizes culture, the pachanga demonstrates that local cultures can exert an equally strong influence on multinational corporations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBusiness and politicszTexas, South. 0aCampaign fundszTexas. 0aCorporate sponsorshipzTexas, South. 0aFestivalszTexas, South. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70690340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796263423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796263/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK